you know , one of the great nographs in traveling , and one of the joys in ethnography is to live with the people who can remember the old days , and the ones who still feel their past in the wind , touch them on the rain , taste them in the bitter leaves of the plants .
just knowing that jaguar shamanas are still traveling beyond the milky way , or the meaning of the myths of the elders of the inuit still matter , or that in the himalayas , the buddhist still trace the breath of the dharma means calling the central revelation of anthropology into mind , which is the idea that the world in which we live , not only exists in an absolute sense , but as a model of reality , as a consequence of a certain set of possibilities that successfully chose our generations .
and of course , we all share the same adaptation needs .
we &apos;re all born . we bring children to the world .
we go through initiation rituals .
we need to deal with the unstoppable separation of death , and so we shouldn &apos;t surprise ourselves that we all sing , dancing and art .
but what &apos;s interesting is the unique sound of the song , the rhythm of the dance in every culture .
it doesn &apos;t matter whether it &apos;s the penan in the forests of borneo , or the voodoo acolyths in haiti , or the warriors in the cairut-desert of northern kenya , the curoculum in the andean , or a caravan in the middle of the sahara . this is the collapse i happened to be traveling to the desert a month ago , or even a yak shepherd hanging on the qomolma desert , everest , the mother of the world .
all these people teach us that there are other existentials , different ways of thinking , different ways of orienting the earth .
and this is an idea that , if you think about it , can only fulfill you with hope .
together , the world &apos;s countless cultures form a web of spiritual and cultural life that wraps the earth and for the good of the earth as important as the biological web that you know as a biosphere .
you can think of this cultural web as an ethnosphere , and ethnosphere can be defined as the total sum of all thoughts and dreams , myths of ideas , inspiration and intuitions that have been defined by the human imagination since the beginning of consciousness .
the ethnosphere is the great legacy of humanity .
it &apos;s the symbol of all of what we are and what we are capable of as an amazingly wiser species .
and just like the biosphere was removed , this was happening with the ethnosphere -- only at greater speed .
no biologist , for example , would argue that 50 percent or more of all species are just about to die out , because it &apos;s just not true . and yet , this -- the most apocalyptic scenarium in the field of biodiversity -- is barely what we know to be the most optimistic scenarium in the field of cultural diversity .
and the key indicator of this is the extinction of languages .
when each of you was born in this room , 6,000 languages were spoken on earth .
now a language is not just the sum of the vocabulary or a series of grammacreature .
a language is a expression of the human mind .
it &apos;s a means where the soul of a certain culture finds access to the material world .
every language is like an old-fashioned forest of the mind , a turning point , an idea , an ecosystem of spiritual possibilities .
and of those 6,000 languages , today , while we &apos;re sitting in monterey , half of them are no longer whispered into the ears of children .
they &apos;re not taught anymore . that means that when nothing &apos;s done , they &apos;re actually dead .
what could be more lonely than being surrounded by silence , to be one of the last people talking to your language , have no way to pass on the wisdom of the ancestors , or to expect the hope of children ?
and yet , this terrible destiny actually happens to someone anywhere on earth , about every two weeks , because every two weeks , an older person dies and takes the last syllable of an old language into the grave .
and i know some of you say , &quot; isn &apos;t it better ? &quot; would the world not be a better place if we all talked just one language ? &quot; and i say , &quot; well , let &apos;s be yoruba . let them be cantonesic .
let &apos;s be willii . &quot;
and then you would suddenly recognize what it would be like if you couldn &apos;t speak your own language .
so today , i want to take you on a journey through the ethnosphere , a short journey through the ethnosphere , to try to understand what &apos;s actually gone wrong .
now there are some of us who kind of forget that when i say &quot; different possibilities of being , &quot; i mean really different possibilities of being .
for example , take this child of barasana in the northwest of the amazon , the people of the anakonda , believe that they came up mythologically with the milky way across the east in the belly of sacred snakes .
this is a people who are not cognitively distinguished between the colors of blue and green , because the sky scene is equated to the forest that people depend on .
they have a strange language and a marriage rule called the linguistic exogamy : you have to marry somebody who speaks another language .
all of this is rooted in the mythological past , and the strange thing about these big houses , which are spoken because of the mischehen six or seven languages , but is that you never hear anybody who learns a language .
you just listen and start talking .
or , one of the most fascinating tribes i &apos;ve ever lived with , the waorani in the northeast of ecuador , an amazing people who was first contacted in 1958 peaceful .
in 1957 , five missionary were trying to connect and made a major mistake .
they threw shiny photos of themselves out of the air , which we would as a friendly gesture , forgot that these people from the rainforest in their lives had never seen anything two-dimensional .
they took these photographs off the forest floor , tried to see behind the face or the character , found nothing , and concluded that this was business cards of the devil , and they killed the five missionaries with the spear .
but the waorani were not just killing outsiders with the spear .
they drilled through each other .
54 percent of the deaths were happening through drilling .
we followed geneaology eight generations , and we found two cases of natural death , and when we asked people about it a little bit about it , they admitted that one of the people had gotten so old that he died because of his age , and we still killed him with the spear .
but at the same time , they had a clear knowledge of the forest that was amazing .
their hunters were able to smell the urine of an animal from 40 steps and determine what animal species this one belonged to .
in the early &apos; 80s , i got a really amazing task when my professor at harvard asked me if i was interested in going to haiti and infiltrating the secret societies that were the foundation of the strength of duvalier and tonton macoutes and the poison that was used to make sure of zombies .
