here &apos;s a photograph i took in the northern end of the baffin islands when i went to narwhal hunt with inuits , and this man , olaya , told me a wonderful story of his grandfather .
the canadian government has not always gone very well with the inuit , and for the 50th years in the establishment of our rule , they have been forced to move in settlements .
the grandfather of this old man refused .
the family who was afraid of his life took all the guns and all the tools .
now you have to know that the inuit is not afraid of the cold . they used it to advantage .
the gliders of their slits were originally made from fish that was wrapped in caribbean skin .
the man &apos;s grandfather was not afraid of the arctic night or the blow storm .
he hatched out , dropped his pants from abalone fur and defeated them in his hand , and when the feces started freezing , he shaped them into the shape of a knife .
he sprayed saliva on the sides of the staircase , and when it was frozen completely , it amazed a dog with it .
he contains the dog , and he improvised a dishes , took the dog &apos;s skeleton and improvised a sled , relaxed another dog , and descended on the ice sheets with the dye knife on the belt .
so you can do something from nothing .
and this is a symbol of the resistance of the inuit and all the indigenous people in the world .
