i &apos;m going to tell you some things about my book that , as i hope , are in harmony with other things that you &apos;ve already heard , and i &apos;m going to try and make some connections if you haven &apos;t noticed them .
i want to start with what i call an official dogma .
official dogma of what ?
official belief of all western industrialized societies .
official dogma works this way : if our goal is to maximize our citizens &apos; public well-being , it &apos;s mostly because of the maximizing of the freedom of the individual .
the reason for that is that freedom is good in itself , valuable , meaningful , a viable assumption for the human .
when people have freedom , each of us is about doing the things that maximize our public good and nobody has to decide for us .
the way to maximize freedom is to maximize choice .
the more choices people have , the more freedom they have , and the more freedom they have , the more they have .
this is , i think , so deeply anchored in our water supply that nobody would ever mind questioning it .
and it &apos;s also deeply rooted in our lives .
i &apos;m going to give you some examples of what makes us modern progress .
this is my supermarket . this is not a big one .
i just want to say a little bit about salatdressing for a second .
there are 175 dressings in my supermarket , if you don &apos;t count the 10 different extra olive oil and you have 12 balsamico that you could buy to make a large number of your own salad of dessings , in the improbable case that none of the 175 in the store is right for you .
so this is what the supermarket is like .
and then you go to the consumer electronics business to put together a stereo -- speakers , cd players , a cassette player , radio , amplified . and in this one electronics business , there are so many stereo .
we can assemble 6.5 million different stereo plants from the components offered in this one business .
you have to admit that this is a big selection .
in other areas -- the world of communication .
there was a time when i was a boy , you could have every telephone provider you wanted as long as he came from ma bell .
they rented your phone . they didn &apos;t buy it . they bought it .
one consequence was that the telephone was never broken .
these days are over .
we have now almost an infinite selection of phones , especially in the mobile world .
these are the mobile phones of the future .
my favorite one is in the middle -- mp3 playwright , wee-haired trimmer and crd br√©e faccles .
and if you haven &apos;t seen this in your business yet , you can be sure you &apos;re going to be soon .
and what it does is it makes people walk into business and ask that question .
do you know what the answer to that question is ?
the answer is no .
it &apos;s not possible to buy a cell phone that doesn &apos;t do too much .
in other aspects of life that are much more significant than buying objects , the same explosion of choice is true .
health care -- it &apos;s no longer the case in the united states that you go to the doctor , and the doctor tells you what to do .
instead , you go to the doctor , and the doctor tells you , we could do a , or we could do b .
a has these benefits and risks .
b has these benefits and risks . what do you want to do ?
and they say , &quot; doctor , what do i do ? &quot;
the doctor says a has these benefits and risks , and b has those benefits and risks .
what do you want to do ?
and if you said , &quot; if you were me , doctor , what would you do ? &quot;
the doctor says , &quot; but i &apos;m not you . &quot;
the result is -- we call it patient autonomy . it sounds like a good thing , but in reality , a shift in responsibility for making decisions from somebody who knows something -- namely , the doctor -- to someone who knows nothing and is highly ill , and therefore not to make a decision -- namely , the patient .
