his job is to create the conditions that existed less than a billionth of a second after the universe -- and this is up to 600 million times within a second .
it &apos;s just breathtaking ambition .
this is the machine underneath geneva .
we take pictures of these mini-big bangs in detectors .
this is what i &apos;m working on . this is called an atlas detector -- 44 meters wide , 22 meters in diameter .
here &apos;s a spectacular picture of the atlas in construction so you can see the scale .
on september 10 , last year , the machine was on for the first time .
and this picture was taken by atlas .
it caused immense jupiter in the control room .
it &apos;s a picture of the first radiation particle that returned all the way around the lhc , then deliberately collided with some of the lhc to allow a rain of particles to bounce into the detector .
in other words , when we saw this image on september 10 , we knew that the machine works , which is a big triumph .
i don &apos;t know if this created the biggest july , or this , when someone went to google side and found the front page like this .
