about a week later , there was a problem with the machine that had to do with these wires here -- these golden wires here .
these wires lead 13-thousand ampses when the machine is running to power .
well , the engineers of you will look at them and say , &quot; no , they don &apos;t . these are little wires . &quot;
they can do that because if you cool them down very far , they become what &apos;s called superconductors .
so at minus 271 degrees , colder than the room between the stars , these wires can hold the tension .
in one of the connections between nine thousand magnets at the lhc , there was a manuscript .
so the wires heat slightly and 13-thousand ampers suddenly met electrical resistance .
this was the result .
now , this is all even more amazing if you can imagine that the magnets weigh over 20 tons and shifted by about a foot .
so we damaged about 50 of the magnets .
and they had to remove what we were doing .
we reconditioned them , we repaired them .
you &apos;re all back on your way back now .
by the end of march , the lhc will be again operational .
we &apos;re going to be able to turn it on , and expect to be able to collect first data in june or july , and continue our journey to find out what the building blocks of the universe are .
