as a computer scientist , inspired by the kind of way we interact with real objects -- with my professional adviser patti and my colleague jeevan kalanithi , i began to wonder : what if we used computers that would be like a mouse tip that moves like a digital fingertip on a flat surface of the work -- what if we could intervene with both hands and intervene data physically and arrange it the way we want it ?
this question was so poignant that we decided to explore the answer and evolved sift .
in short , a siftable is an interactive computer the size of a cookie .
you can be moved by your hand , you can perceive each other , you can detect your movements , and you have a screen and a radio receiver .
more importantly , they &apos;re physical , so you can only move them out of your hands and your access .
and the sift is an example of a new generation of tools for manipulation of digital data .
and if these tools become more physical and become more conscious of their movements , recognize each other and see the intricacies of our approach , then we can start to explore new and entertaining interactions .
