the interpret work .
music as a language .
in the description of my talk , i , as an interpreter , stands to understand me as a translator , in english words .
interpreters are translators of the written notes in clinical music .
that , as a translator , you have to understand not just the word &quot; text &quot; into a different language , but you have to understand the deeper sense of words and wortzus bias to make it a useful translation , anyone who has to do with foreign languages .
translate from german to english can require more knowledge once in a while when you &apos;re talking about poetry or even about poetry .
but it &apos;s alien to layman , what we do to musicians with our music language .
as an interpreter of a piece of music , i have only the written notes .
you think that the composer has written into the notes exactly everything he came up with .
in fact , the notes are very vague and inaccurate .
these notes are about as accurate or as inaccurate as a verbal , even though very seemingly penile , description of a landscape .
because in this verbal landscape description , the smell is not to smell the flowers , the degree of the founder , just to guess not to hear the sawdust of the wind .
that means that the interpret has to translate these unprecedented notes of sound into another , which is audible , concrete , non-verbal music language .
today i want to leave you with what i used to translate music , which is interpreting , again , into a verbal language .
so basically , a translation of the translation .
so i prefer to do the whole thing in german , because if i had to translate it into english , it would be equivalent to me to translation the translation of translation .
so , the one that the music works for me is kind of like the spoken language .
the written notes have the function of the letters of a script .
so it &apos;s not enough to just learn to read notes and press the keys corresponding on the piano or the right place on a violin string .
because these would be just the letters that you learned to paint .
the point of the letters is that you only recognize the language of it .
so for the learning process of music , at least as long as it is for spoken language .
now , there &apos;s a case where you learn it for practice , you just passively understand it , or you can also talk to the musical mother linguists .
the interpreter work begins rather like a theater director &apos;s work .
after first you &apos;ve chosen a piece of play , because you &apos;re excited about it , you go back and look at the origin of composition .
you collect information about the piece in the secondary literature .
you read in the letters , the pockets , the notes , or if there are words , of composers themselves .
you study the works that he composed before and after .
you compare it .
the motivations of writing it .
how and what did he feel ?
what were its circumstances , like society and politics ?
all of this is what i &apos;m interested in .
you think into that time , for example , by looking at contemporary images or reading literature .
but also , over time , as an interpreter , you have a rich knowledge to play the composer you play more often , and it &apos;s going to make you feel easier and easier to think into it .
the composer becomes more and more to the friend you live with .
his cause of writing the piece becomes more and more to my personal cause of playing it .
now that the notes are an accurate record of the composer , but only a framework , now i &apos;m applying this framework to refill it with meaning and meaning .
i then say in my own words , what might be written between this framework ?
i play games explaining what these notes might have .
now for me and for the composers , and what you might mean for them today .
every sound , every phrase , gets a sense of it , because i feel it myself , because it comes out of my own right now .
it has to be coherent to me in this room and now , otherwise i can &apos;t convince my audience that this is my cause .
it &apos;s always a very happy concert over and over again , if i may have the experience , the piece that i &apos;ve worked out for so long in advance , how to experience new .
how to experience a happy new day over and over again , although with the same rituals of life , getting up , breakfast , going to work , i &apos;m doing the same piece over and over again .
i grew back a day when the seasons change , my pulse goes slower than in the morning , in a concert hall , takes longer for the sound to come back than at home .
i &apos;m going to notice the breathing of the audience , consciously or unconsciously .
all of this affects me , and all of this also affects my experience with composition .
