when steve lopez , columnist of the los angeles times , went through the streets one day in the center of los angeles , he heard a wonderful music .
she came from a man , an african-american , sympathetic , rau , homeless , who played on a violin , who had only two strings .
many of you will know the story , because from steves &apos;s article on it later , a book that was filmed again , with robert downey junior when steve lopez and jamie foxx was a nathaniel anthony ayers , the contrabassistant who was studied at the juilliard conservatory , and whose promising career was tragically finished by his paranoid schizophrenia early on .
nathaniel left juilliard , suffered a breakdown , and 30 years later he lived as homeless on the streets of skid row in the center of los angeles .
i recommend all of you to read steves book or to watch the film so that not only did you understand the wonderful connection that was born between these two men , but also how music helped to connect that , and how it eventually was the instrument when that word game was allowed to get mithalf , nathaniel away from the street .
i met mr ayers in 2008 , two years ago , in the walt disney hall .
he had just heard a demo by beethoven &apos;s first and fourth symphony and came behind the stage to imagine myself .
he spoke in a very hot and social note about yo-yo ma and hillary clinton , and how the dodgers would never get into baseball world series , and all of this because of the first violin in the last sentence of beethoven &apos;s fourth symphony .
we came up with the theme of music , and a few days later i got an email saying nathaniel was interested in me for self-training .
i have to mention that nathaniel was rejecting medical treatment because he was already treated with electric shocks and thorazine and handcuffs , a trauma he pursued all his life .
as a result , he &apos;s especially vulnerable to these schizophrenic phases now , which are sometimes so bad , and he disappears for days in the streets of skid row , always exposed to this horror and torture of his own mind .
and in exactly one of those lovely stages , nathaniel was when we started with our first lectures in the walt disney art hall , and he had this irre flatter in his eyes and worked completely out .
he talked about invisible demons and smoke and how someone wanted to poison him in their sleep .
i was afraid , not opinion , but i was afraid that i could lose him , that he could sink into one of his states , and that i could destroy his relationship with the violin when i started talking about pitches and arpeggios and other exciting forms of didactic gardening .
so i just started playing .
i played the first sentence by beethoven &apos;s violin concert .
and as i was playing , i noticed that in nathin &apos;s eyes , a complete change was happening .
it was like it was under the impact of an invisible doctor &apos;s disease , a chemical reaction whose catalyst was my game .
nathaniels of manic anger turned into understanding , into a quiet curiosity and courage .
and as with a miracle , he took his violin and he started playing some clips of violin concerts , and then he asked me to end up playing : menu son , tshaikowski , sibelius .
we then started talking about music , from bach to beethoven , brahms , bruckner and all the other bs , from bartok to esa pekka salons .
and i realized that he had not only an encyclopedic knowledge about music , but connected it to a close personal relationship .
he talked about her with a passion and an understanding i &apos;ve only known of my colleagues in the philharmony of los angeles .
by playing music and talking about music , from this paranoid , confused man who had just moved through the streets of los angeles , a loving , educated , sketched , skilled musician in juilliard .
music is medicine . music changes us .
for nathaniel , music means mental health .
because the music allows him to reform his thoughts and delusions with his imagination and creativity into something real .
and so he escapes its tormented state .
i understood that this is the nature of art .
that &apos;s why we &apos;re doing music : so that we can do something that &apos;s inside us all deep , our emotions , through our artistic lens , can form through our creativity to reality .
and the reality of that expression reaches us all , and moves , inspired and united .
in terms of nathaniel , the music brought him back into a community of friends .
the redeeming power of music brought him back to a family of musicians who understood his talent and looked at him .
and i &apos;m going to keep making music with nathaniel , whether it &apos;s at the walt disney , reverberation , or skid row , because he reminds me of why i became a musician .
