today i &apos;m going to talk to you about energy and climate .
and this may be surprising , because my full-time work at the foundation is all about vaccines and seeds , about the things we have to invent and deliver to the poorest two billion to make a better life .
but energy and climate are extremely important for these people , in fact , more important than anyone else on the planet .
climate degradation means that their crops will not grow for many years , we will rain too much or too little . things will change the way their fragile environment cannot change .
this leads to starvation . it leads to uncertainty . it leads to riots .
so , climate change is going to be terrible for you .
and also , for them , the energy cycle is very important .
in fact , if you could only reduce price from one thing , poverty reduction would be energy at far the most effective .
well , the energy cycle has fallen over time .
in fact , progress society is based on energy advances .
coal evolution pushed the industrial revolution , and even in the 20th century , there was a rapid case of electricity , and that &apos;s why we have refrigerators , climate conditioners , we can create modern materials and do so many things .
so we &apos;re in a wonderful situation with electricity in the rich world .
but if we reduce the price -- let &apos;s cut the price down -- we &apos;ll hit a new barrier , and that barrier will depend on co2 .
co2 heats the planet , and the equation for co2 is actually quite clear .
they add the out-of-the-box co2 that leads to temperature increases , and that temperature increases has some very negative consequences , effects on the weather , and perhaps worse , the indirect consequence that the natural ecosystems can &apos;t adapt to such rapid changes , and therefore whole systems collapse .
well , the exact relationship between a co2 rise and the result of that is that there are a few ambiguous things , but there are not very many .
and there &apos;s certainly ambiguity about how bad these consequences are going to be , but they &apos;re going to be extremely bad .
i asked the top scientists several times , &quot; do we really have to get down to close zero ?
isn &apos;t it enough half or a quarter ? &quot;
the answer is : until we get close to zero , the temperature will continue to increase .
so it &apos;s a big challenge .
it &apos;s very different from saying we have a three-foot truck that has to come from under a three-foot bridge , and then you can squeeze that from underneath .
this has to be down to zero .
well , we &apos;re emitting a lot of carbon dioxide every year over 26 billion tons .
every american , about 20 tons . people from poor countries , less than one .
on average , it &apos;s about five tons for everyone on the planet .
and somehow we have to create changes that reduce that to zero .
it &apos;s gone up constant .
just different economic changes have affected it at all , and we have to go up and down from the increase to zero .
this equation has four factors . a little bit of multiplication . you have this thing on the left -- co2 , which you want to get to zero , and that &apos;s going to depend on the number of services every human being uses on average , the average energy for every service and co2 that &apos;s emitted per unit of energy .
so let &apos;s look at every factor and think about how we get that to zero .
probably one of these numbers has to get very close to zero .
now this is basic algebra , but let &apos;s go through it .
first , we have the population .
today , 6.8 billion people live .
and it &apos;s heading towards nine billion . it &apos;s moving to nine billion .
if we were to very successful with new vaccines , health care and reproduction medicine , we could probably reduce 10 percent to 15 percent , but right now we &apos;re seeing a slope by 1.3 .
the second factor is the services we use .
that includes everything , the food we eat , clothing , television , heating .
that &apos;s very good things , and poverty reduction is about making these services available to almost everybody on the planet .
it &apos;s great that this number goes up .
in the rich world , in the top billion , we might be able to eliminate and use less , but on average , that number will go up every year , and so the total number of services will double , the number of services that are provided per person .
here we see a very basic service . is there light at home so you can read the homework ?
and these students don &apos;t have it , so they go out and read their school assignments under the street .
well , with effectiveness , the e , the energy per service , there &apos;s finally good news .
we have something that doesn &apos;t go up .
because of different outcomes in the light sector , through different autotypes , through new ways of building buildings , there are many services where some of the power services are reduced by 90 percent .
in other services , like fertilizer production , 105 : 05 : 05 : 05 : 05 : 05 : 58,000 or air traffic or air traffic , the space for improvement is much smaller .
in total , if we &apos;re optimistic , maybe we &apos;ll get a reduction by a factor three or maybe even by a factor six .
but the first three factors , we &apos;ve gone from 26 billion to perhaps the very best 13 billion tons . and that &apos;s just not enough !
so let &apos;s look at the fourth factor -- and this is going to be a key factor -- that &apos;s the amount of co2 emitted per unit of energy .
it &apos;s a question of , can you get this to zero ?
if you burn coal , no .
if you burn natural gas , no .
almost every electricity manufacturing method today emitts co2 , except renewables and nuclear power .
so , what we need to do at a global level is create a new system .
we need energy miracles .
now , when i use the term &quot; wonder , &quot; i don &apos;t mean the impossible .
the microprocessor is a miracle . the pc is a miracle .
the internet and service is a miracle .
people here contributed to the development of many of these miracles .
there &apos;s usually no deadline that you need a miracle to have a particular date .
usually you &apos;re just wrong , and some of them come , some of them don &apos;t .
in this case , we have to give full gas and get a miracle in very short order .
