and then what do you do with the waste ?
because even though it &apos;s not very big , there &apos;s a lot of concerns .
so three very difficult problems that you might have to solve , and that &apos;s why you should work on .
i &apos;ve summarized the last three of the five .
it &apos;s renewables , as they often call them .
and they also have -- although it &apos;s great , they don &apos;t need fuel -- they have some disadvantages .
one , the energy density that these technologies are generating is dramatically lower than the power plants .
these are energy farms , you talk about many square kilometers , a thousand times more land than a normal power station .
and these sources also underlie disruptions .
the sun doesn &apos;t shine all day , it doesn &apos;t shine every day , and the wind doesn &apos;t always fall .
so if you &apos;re dependent on these sources , you have a way to get the energy in times when it &apos;s not available .
so there are big prices here . there are challenges in transmission , for example , when we say that the energy source is outside the country , you don &apos;t just need the technology , you also need to deal with the risk of where the energy comes from .
and there &apos;s the problems of storage .
and to show you the dimension , i looked at all kinds of batteries that are made : the cars , computers , flashlights , for everything . and i compared that to the amount of electronic energy that the world uses , i found that all the batteries that we now produce could store less than 10 minutes of total energy .
so we need a major breakthrough here , something that will be 100 better than the approaches at the moment .
that &apos;s not impossible , but it &apos;s not that easy .
this is what happens when you try to bring these interrupted sources about saying 20 percent -- 30 percent of the consumption .
