a few years ago , here at ted , peter skillman introduced a design competition called the marshmallow challenge .
the idea is pretty simple . four teams have to build the large-scale free-standing structure with 20 spaghetti , about a meter tape , about 1-foot thread and a marshmallow .
the marshmallow must be on top .
and , although it seems really simple , it &apos;s actually really hard , because it urges people to work very quickly .
and so i thought this was an interesting idea , and i turned it into a design shop .
it was a huge success .
since i &apos;ve been doing about 70 workshops around the world , with students , developers and architects , even with ctos of fortune 50-company , and there &apos;s something about this kind of task that allows deep insights into the nature of collaboration , and i want to share with you some of them .
most people usually start to orient themselves in terms of the task .
you talk about it , you think about what it &apos;s going to look like , you &apos;re running around power .
then you spend a little bit of time in planning and organization , sketching and putting spaghetti out .
they spend most of their time in assembling continually growing structures .
and finally , just before you have time , somebody takes the marshmallow and you put it gently on the top , you step back and you say , &quot; ta-da ! &quot; you admire your work .
but then , almost always , what happens is that the ta-da becomes a &quot; uh-oh &quot; because the weight of the marshmallov causes the whole thing to bend and collapse .
there are a number of people who have much more uh-oh moments than others , and the worst of all are fresh bwl graduates .
they lie , they cheat , they cheat , they &apos;re confused , and they produce really droughts .
and of course , there are teams who have much more ta-da shapes , and among the best are fresh allies of kindergarten .
and this is pretty amazing .
as peter told us , not only did they produce the highest towers , but also the most interesting structures of all .
what you might ask is , how does that happen ? why ? what about them ?
and peter says , &quot; none of the kids spend time being the head of the spaghetti gmbh . &quot;
they don &apos;t spend time in power fighting .
there &apos;s another reason .
and that is that bwl students have been trained to find the right plan , ok ?
and then realizing him .
what happens when you put the marshmallow on the top , you don &apos;t have time , and what happens ?
it &apos;s a crisis .
sounds familiar , what ?
what kindergarten kids do differently is they start with the marshmallow and build prototypes , successful prototypes , always with the marshmallow at the top , so that they have a multi-fold opportunity to fix bloody prototypes .
constructors recognize this kind of collaboration as the core of an iterative process .
and with every attempt , the kids get immediate feedback about what works and what doesn &apos;t work .
so the performance of working with prototypes is a lot -- but let &apos;s see how different teams act .
most of them are about 500 inches , bwl students are creating half of them , lawyers are a little more , but not much , kindergarten kids are better than the adults .
who is the most successful one ?
architects and engineers , fortunately .
one m is the highest thing i &apos;ve seen .
and why ? because they understand triangles and self-replicating geometric patterns are the key to build stable structures .
ceos are a little bit above average . but this is where it gets interesting .
if you put an executive administrator on the team , they get significantly better .
it &apos;s incredible . you look around and you see , &quot; this team is going to win . &quot;
you can predict that . why is that happening ?
because they have special skills of processing .
you run the process , you understand it .
and that team that rules and looks at the work will significantly improve the performance of the team .
specialized skills and processing skills and their combination lead to success .
if you have 10 teams that typically do happen , you get about six who have stable structures .
now i tried something exciting .
i thought we &apos;d bring the poker &apos;s use in a moment .
so i offered a $ 10,000 prize in software for the winners .
what do you think happened to these design students ?
what was the result ?
this is what happened . not one team had a stable structure .
if anyone had built a two-inch construction , they would have worn the price home .
so isn &apos;t it interesting that high competitions have a strong effect ?
we repeated that exercise with the same students .
now , what do you think happened ?
now they understood the advantage of prototyping .
so from the same bad team , one of the best .
they produced the highest construction in the least time .
so there are profound lessons for us about the nature of drive and success .
you might ask : why would somebody actually invest time creating a marshmallow challenge ?
the reason is , i &apos;m helping create digital tools and processes to help teams create cars , video games and visual imagery .
and what the marshmallow challenge does is it helps them identify hidden assumptions .
because frankly , every project has its own marshmallow .
the challenge is to have a shared experience , a common language , or basic , to build the right prototype .
and that &apos;s the value of this experience , this simple exercise .
and those of you who are interested in it can visit marshmallowchallenge.com .
it &apos;s a blog where you see the marshmallows being built .
there &apos;s a step-by-step manual there .
you find crazy examples from all over the world how people optimize and refine the system .
there are also world record .
and the basic lesson , i think , is that construction is actually a commitment sport .
it requires that we all do our senses on the task and that we use our thinking optimal , like our emotions and our actions , in the challenge that we face .
and sometimes a small prototype of this experience is everything it takes to take us from a uh-oh to a ta-da moment .
and that can make a big difference .
