everybody &apos;s talking today about happiness .
i &apos;ve let some people count the number of books that were published with happiness in the last five years , and they &apos;ve spent about 40 years , and there &apos;s a lot more .
there &apos;s a tremendous wave of interest in happiness among researchers .
there &apos;s a lot of happiness coaching .
everybody would like to make people happier .
but despite all this flood of work , there are several cognitive traits that make it almost impossible to think clearly about happiness .
and my talk today is going to be mostly about these cognitive failures .
this is true of layman thinking about your own happiness , and it &apos;s true of scientists thinking about happiness , because it turns out we &apos;re just as mess as anyone else .
the first of these falls is a contradiction to admit complexity .
it turns out the word happiness is just not a useful word anymore , because we apply it to too many different things .
i think there &apos;s a certain meaning that we could confine it to , but by and large , this is something we need to give up , and we &apos;re going to have to take on the complicated view of what well-being is .
the second trap is a change in experience and memory : it &apos;s basically between being happy in his life and being happy about his life or happy with his life .
and these are two very different concepts , and they &apos;re both together in the idea of happiness .
and the third is the concentration illusion , and that &apos;s the unfortunate fact that we can &apos;t think about a circumstance that affects well-being without distorting its meaning .
i mean , this is a real cognitive trap .
there &apos;s just no way to get it right .
now i &apos;d like to start with an example of someone who had a question and answer session after one of my lectures , who had a story . &#91; unclear &#93; he said he heard a symphony , and it was absolutely glorious music , and at the very end of the recording there was a terrible circulating sound .
and then he added in , really quite emotional , and that ruined the whole experience .
but it didn &apos;t .
what it ruined was the memories of the experience .
he had the experience .
he &apos;d had 20 minutes of glorious music .
they didn &apos;t count because he was left with a memory , the memory was ruined , and the memory was all he had to keep .
what this really tells us is that we could think about ourselves and other people in the sense of two types of self .
there &apos;s a living self that lives in the present , and the present is able to experience the past , but it &apos;s basically just the present .
it &apos;s the living self that the doctor primes -- you know , when the doctor asks , &quot; does it hurt now when i fiber you here ? &quot;
and then there &apos;s a memory of self , and the memory itself is the one that counts and receives the story of our lives , and it &apos;s the one that the doctor responds to by asking the question , &quot; how did you feel recently ? &quot;
or , &quot; what was your journey to albania ? &quot; or something like that .
these are two very different units , the living self and the memorizing self , and confusing the two is part of the very different of the sense of happiness .
well , the memory itself is a storyteller .
and this really starts with a fundamental reaction to our memories -- it starts immediately .
we don &apos;t just tell stories when we make ourselves telling stories .
our memory tells us stories , which means what we can keep from our experiences is a story .
and let them start with an example .
there &apos;s an old study .
these are real patients undergoing a painful procedure .
i &apos;m not going to go into the details . she &apos;s no longer painful today , but she was painful when this study was done in the 1990s .
they were asked to report every 60 seconds about their pain .
and here are two patients . these are their records .
and they &apos;re asked , &quot; who here has suffered more ? &quot;
and that &apos;s a very simple question .
patient b clearly suffered more . his reflection was longer , and every minute of pain the patient a had patient b and more .
but now there &apos;s another question : &quot; how much did these patients think they were suffering ? &quot;
and here &apos;s a surprise .
and the surprise is that patient a had a much worse reminder of the gut reflection than patient b .
the stories of the gut reflections were different , and because a very critical part of the story is how it ends .
and none of these stories are very building or great -- but one of them is this clear ...
but one of them is far worse than the other .
and the one that was worse was where the pain was at the very end of its peak . it &apos;s a bad story .
how do we know ?
because we asked these people about their gut reflection , and also much later , &quot; how bad was the whole thing going on ? &quot;
and it was much worse for a than b to remember .
well , this is a direct conflict between the living self and the remembering self .
from the point of view of the living self , b clearly had a worse time .
now , what you could do with patient a , and we actually did clinical experiments , and it &apos;s been done , and it works , you could actually expand the patient &apos;s reflection by just letting the tube in there without shaking too much on it .
this is going to lead the patient to suffer , but only a little bit less than before .
and if you do that for a few minutes , you &apos;ve caused the living self to be worse off by a patient , and you &apos;ve caused the memory of the patient to be much better off from the patient a , because now you &apos;ve given patient a a a better story about your experience .
what &apos;s a story through ?
and this is true of the stories that memory provides us , and it &apos;s true of the stories that we invent .
what a story is characterized by outbreaks , meaningful moments and ends .
end is very , very important , and in this case , it dominated the end .
well , the living self lives its life continuously .
it has moments of life , one by one .
and you ask , what happens to these moments ?
and the answer is really simple . they &apos;re lost forever .
i mean , most of the moments of our lives -- and i &apos;ve calculated this -- you know , the psychological present is true of about three seconds , which means , you know , there are about 600 million of them in a month . in a month , there are about 600,000 . most of them don &apos;t leave any trace .
most of you are completely ignored by the memory of yourself .
and yet , you get the sense that you should count , that what happened during that moments of life is our lives .
it &apos;s the limited resource we consume while we &apos;re in this world .
and how we would use it seems to be important , but that &apos;s not the story that keeps the memory of ourselves .
so we have the memory itself and the living self , and they &apos;re really quite different .
the biggest difference between them is the treatment of time .
from the point of view of the living self , if you have a vacation and the second week is just as good as the first week , then the second vacation is twice as good as the one-week vacation .
that &apos;s not how it works at all for the memory itself .
for the memory of itself , a two-week vacation is hardly better than the weekly vacation , because there are no new memories to be added .
they haven &apos;t changed the story .
and this is actually how time is the critical variable that distinguishes a memory of self from a heritage living self , and time affects this story very little .
now , memory itself makes more than remembering and telling stories .
it &apos;s actually the one that makes decisions , because if you have a patient who had , say , two gut reflections in two different surgeons and decides which one to vote , then the one who chooses the memory is less bad , and that &apos;s the surgeon who &apos;s going to be selected .
the living self has no voice in that choice .
we don &apos;t actually choose between experiences . we choose between memories of experiences .
and even when we think about the future , we don &apos;t usually think about our future as an experience .
we think about our future as a foreseeable memories .
and basically , you can look at this , you know , as a tyranny of memory itself , and you can think of the memory of yourself as one that kind of draws the living self through experiences that don &apos;t need the living self .
i have the impression that when we do vacation , it &apos;s very often the case , which means we tend to make vacation in the service of memory itself .
and that &apos;s a little hard to justify , i think .
i mean , how much do we consume of our memories ?
that &apos;s one of the explanations that &apos;s been given to the dominance of memory itself .
and when i think about it , i think of a vacation that we did a few years ago in antarctica , which was clearly the best vacation i &apos;d ever had , and i think quite often about how often i think of other vacations .
and i &apos;ve probably gone from my memories to this three-week journey , i would say for about 25 minutes in the last four years .
now , if i had ever opened the folder with the 600 pictures in it , i would have spent another hour .
