there seems to be a disagreement .
well , i may be a little extreme , you know , how little appetite do i have on the toes of memories , but even if you make more of them , there &apos;s a real question . why do we give memories so much weight in the course of the weight that we give experiences ?
so i want you to think about a thought experiment .
imagine your next vacation , you know , at the end of vacation , all of your images are devastated , and you get an amnesiac drug so you won &apos;t remember anything .
now , would you choose the same vacation ?
and if you picked another vacation , there &apos;s a conflict between your two types of self , and you have to think about how you decide this conflict , and that &apos;s really not obvious at all , because if you think about time , in terms of memories , you might get a different answer .
why we choose the vacation that we choose is a problem that we choose with a choice between the two species of self .
well , the two types of self throw two terms of happiness up .
there are actually two concepts of happiness that we can use , one per self .
so you can ask : how happy is the living self ?
and then you would ask : how happy are the moments of the living self ?
and they &apos;re all -- happiness for moments is a pretty complicated process .
what are the emotions that can be measured ?
and by the way , we &apos;re able to get a pretty good idea about the happiness of the living self over time .
if you ask about the happiness of the memory itself , it &apos;s a very different thing .
this is not about how happy a person lives .
it &apos;s about how happy or delighted the person is when they think about their lives .
very different term .
anyone who doesn &apos;t tell these terms will screw up the exploration of happiness , and i &apos;m one of the many researchers about well-being that have screwed the exploration of happiness in this very same way .
the distinction between the happiness of the living self and the happiness of the memory itself has been recognized in the last few years , and now you &apos;re trying to measure the two separate .
the gallup organization has a global survey where more than half a million people have been asked questions about what they think about their lives and what their experiences are , and there are other efforts in the direction .
so in the last few years , we &apos;ve started to learn about the happiness of the two species of self .
and the main lesson we &apos;ve learned , i think , is that they &apos;re really different .
you can know how happy someone is with your life , and that really doesn &apos;t teach you much about how happy he lives his life and vice versa .
just to give you a sense of correlation , the correlation is about .5 .
what that means is that if you met somebody , and you were to tell them , oh , your father is a two-meter man , how much would you know about your size ?
well , you would know something about its size , but there &apos;s a lot of uncertainty .
they have so much uncertainty .
when i tell you that somebody put their life as eight on a scale of 10 , they have put a lot of uncertainty on how happy they are with their own living selves .
so the correlation is small .
we know something about what the happiness of the happiness itself determines .
we know money is very important , targets are very important .
we know that happiness is mostly about being satisfied with people we like to spend time with people we like .
there are other pleasures , but that &apos;s dominant .
so if you want to maximize the happiness of the two species of self , you &apos;ll end up doing very different things .
the conclusion from what i &apos;ve been saying here is that we really shouldn &apos;t imagine happiness as a replacement of well-being .
it &apos;s a completely different term .
well , very briefly , another reason we can &apos;t clearly think about happiness is that we don &apos;t pay attention to the same things when we think about life and when we actually live .
so if you ask the simple question of how happy people are in california , you &apos;re not going to get the correct answer .
when you ask that question , you think that people in california have to be happier when they say , &quot; ohio . &quot;
and what happens is that when you think about life in california , think about the difference between california and other places , and that difference is , say , in the climate .
well , it turns out that climate is not very important for the living self , and it &apos;s not even very important for the memorial self to decide how happy people are .
now , because the thoughtful self is responsible , you can end up -- some people could end up going to california .
and it &apos;s kind of interesting to pursue what happens to people who move to california in hopes to get happier .
well , your living self will not get happier .
we know that .
but one thing that &apos;s going to happen . you &apos;re going to think you &apos;re happier , because if you think about it , you &apos;re reminded of how awful the weather was in ohio , and you &apos;re going to feel you &apos;ve made the right decision .
it &apos;s very difficult to think about well-being , and i hope i &apos;ve given you a sense of how difficult it is .
