i &apos;m jane mcgonigal . i design video games .
i &apos;ve been developing online games for 10 years now , and my goal for the next decade is to make it as easy to save the world in reality as it is in online games .
i have a plan for it . i want to convince more people , including all of you , to spend more time playing bigger and great games .
we &apos;re now spending three billion hours a week playing online games .
some of you may think , &quot; that &apos;s a lot of time for games . &quot;
maybe a little too much time when you think about how many problems we urge to solve in the real world .
but in fact , my research at the institute of the future is just the opposite .
three billion hours a week are not nearly enough to solve the most urgent problems in the world .
in fact , i believe that if we want to survive the next century on the planet , we need to dramatically increase that time .
i calculated that time is 21 billion hours of play per week .
this seems a little bit wakeful first , so i repeat it to make it work : if we want to solve problems like hunger , poverty , climate change , global conflicts and obesity , i think we need to try to play online for at least 21 billion hours a week to the end of the next decade .
no , i &apos;m really serious about it .
why ? this picture quite precisely describes why i think games are so vital to the survival of the human species in the future . seriously .
this is a portrait of photographer phil toledano .
he wanted to capture the feelings in games , so he &apos;s built a camera before the players .
this is one of the classic expressions in playing .
