one of the areas in which we see this for beipiel , in our culture today , in today &apos;s united states , the battles are over the beginning and the end of life .
we have difficult conversations about what part of the body becomes human , so that it has a different right than the fetal life .
we have very difficult conversations today -- perhaps not as public as in medicine -- about the question of when someone &apos;s dead .
our ancestors used to have never had that hard to fight with the question of when someone was dead .
they &apos;ve stayed a spring under their nose , and when they move , they haven &apos;t buried them yet .
when it didn &apos;t move , you &apos;ve buried it .
but today we are in a situation where we take people &apos;s vital organs and we want to plant them to other people .
and as a consequence , we start fighting the really difficult question of when someone &apos;s dead , and this brings us into a really difficult situation where we don &apos;t have as simple categories as we used to .
now you might think that the whole thing would collapse from categories like me .
i &apos;m politically progressive , i defend people with unusual bodies , but i have to admit i &apos;m nervous .
to understand that these categories are really much more insecure than we thought made me excited .
and it makes me excited about how we think about democracy .
so to tell you about that tension , i have to first know that i &apos;m a big fan of founding fathers .
i know they were racized , i know they were sexest , but they were great .
