it &apos;s because of what happened in 1776 to the founding fathers .
the founding fathers , from my point of view , were the original anatomical activists , and that &apos;s why .
what they proved was an anatomical concept , and they replaced it through another that was radial and beautiful , and 200 years was central to us .
as you all remember , our founding fathers rejected the concept of monarchy , and the monarchy was based on a very simplistic concept of anatomy .
the rulers of the old world had no concept based on dna , but they had a concept of birth on the right .
they had a concept of blue blood .
they were the notion that people who had political power should have this political power because of the inherited blood line from grandfather to son and so on .
the founding fathers proved this idea back and replaced it through a new anatomical concept , and this concept said that all humans were created equally .
they niveled the playfield , and they decided that anatomically , the similarities count , not the differences . and that was very radical .
now they did that in part because they were part of an enlightening system where two things grew together .
democracy grew in , but at the same time science grew in .
if you look at the story of the founding fathers , you realize that many of them were very interested in science , and they were interested in a concept of a naturalist world .
they went from explanations of supernatural form and proven things like a supernatural concept of power back where transmission is based on a very vague concept of birth .
they moved to a natural concept .
and if you look at , for example , the declaration of independence , they talk about nature and the god of nature .
they &apos;re not talking about god and the nature of god .
they talk about the power of nature to tell us who we are .
and as part of that , they gave us a concept that was about anatomical commonalities .
and they really prepared the civil rights movement in a wonderful way .
they didn &apos;t think about it that way , but what they did for us was great .
so what happened years after that ?
for example , women who pursued the election right , the concept of founding fathers , which says that anatomical similarity is more important than the anatomical difference , and said , &quot; we have a uterus and ovaries as a difference enough that we should not be right to vote , the right to own right to own , etc . &quot;
