as an artist , i think the context is very important .
through my work , i &apos;m trying to express that people are not separate from nature and that everything is connected .
for the first time , i was in antarctica , where i saw my first icebergs , almost 10 years ago .
i was struck by awe .
my heart raced , i was dizzy , trying to write what was in front of me .
the icebergs around me were almost 60 meters out of the water , and i could only wonder that this was a snowflake on another snowflake , year after year .
icebergs are born as a calf of a glacier , or by breaking out of ice sheets .
each iceberg has its own individual personality .
they &apos;re clearly interacting with their environment and their experiences .
some people refuse to give up and grab into the bitter end , while others don &apos;t stop and collapse dramatic passion in a seizure .
when you look at an iceberg , you think easily they &apos;re isolated , separated and alone , just like we humans often see .
but the truth is far from it .
as an iceberg melts together , i breathe its temporary atmosphere .
as the iceberg melts , it unleashes mineral drinking water that feeds a lot of life forms .
i &apos;m going to make my images of these icebergs as if i were to make portraits of my ancestors , consciousness , that they exist in these individual moments of this way , and never will exist again .
it &apos;s not a death when they melt ; it &apos;s not an end , but it &apos;s a continuation of their path along the life cycle .
part of the ice in the icebergs that i &apos;m photographing is very young -- a few thousand years old .
and part of the ice is more than 100,000 years old .
the last pictures i &apos;d like to show you are a iceberg that i photographed in kekertsuatsiak in greenland .
