the idea behind the stuxnet computer worm is pretty simple .
we don &apos;t want iran to build the bomb .
the most important post there for nuclear weapons to develop is the uranian incentive facility in nateness .
the gray boxes you see here , these are real-time control systems .
now if we can commit the systems that control the numbers and the valves , we can actually create a lot of problems with the centrifuge .
these gray boxes don &apos;t run with windows software ; they &apos;re based on a completely different technology .
but if we can do it , if we can do it with an effective windows virus on a laptop that &apos;s used by a warning engineer to configure this gray box , we &apos;re in the business .
and this is the planning behind stuxnet .
so we start with a windows drug .
the user data is transferred into the gray box , damaged the centrifuge and the iranian nuclear energy program is delayed -- mission .
this is a child game , right ?
i want to tell you how we figured that out .
when we started our research six months ago , it was completely unknown what the meaning and purpose of this construction was .
the only thing we knew is very , very complicated , in terms of the windows part , the dropperone part , he made countless ceround use of it .
and it seemed something to have to do with these gray boxes , these real-time control systems .
this attracted our attention , and we started a lab project where we infected our environment with stuxnet , and we studied this construct .
and then something funny happened .
stuxnet was like a lab rat that didn &apos;t like our cheese -- sniff it , but didn &apos;t want to eat it .
that made no sense in my eyes .
and after experimenting with different kinds of cheese , i realized this is a target attack .
fully targeted a particular destination .
the dropper is actively fighting around the gray box when a special configuration was discovered , even when the special program that tries to infect is trying to run on that goal .
and if it doesn &apos;t , it doesn &apos;t matter .
so , that really seemed my interest , and we started working with it , almost around the clock , because i thought , well , we don &apos;t know what the goal is .
it could be , for example , a u.s. power plant or an chemical plant in germany .
so we should soon figure out what the goal is .
so we extracted and decommissioned the code of attacks , and we found that it &apos;s built into two digital warheads -- a smaller one and a bigger one .
and we also noticed that they were very professionally constructed by people who obviously had all the insiders available information .
they knew all the bits and bytes they had to attack .
they probably even knew the shoe size of the machine operator .
so they knew everything .
and if you already have the fact that the dropper of stuxnet is complex and high-tech , let me tell you , the user data is a science for you .
it &apos;s much more sophisticated than anything we &apos;ve ever seen .
here &apos;s a clip of this assault code .
we &apos;re talking about -- about 15,000 lines of code .
it looks pretty much like old-fashioned assembly language .
and i want to tell you how we were able to get out of this code .
so for what we first looked for , system-functioning calls were because we know what they &apos;re doing .
and then we looked for tigers and data structures , and we tried to connect them to the real world -- with potential targets in the real world .
so we needed theories about these targets that we could illuminate or disprove .
to set up these theories , let &apos;s remember that it &apos;s definitely high-level sabotage , it has to be a high-quality goal , and very likely it &apos;s in iran , because most infections have been reported .
well , in this area , there aren &apos;t several thousand targets .
it &apos;s basically going out to the bush of nuclear power plants and the incentive facility in nating .
so i said to my assistant , &quot; bring me a list of all the centrifuge experts and power plants from our client tribe . &quot;
and i called them up , and i tapped their knowledge to compare their expertise with what we found in the code and in the data .
and that worked very well .
so , we were able to connect the little digital warhead to the rotor tax .
the rotor is this moving part inside the centrifuge , this black object that you see .
and if you manipulate the speed of this rotor , you &apos;re actually able to crack the rotor and eventually even let the centrifuge explode .
what we also found out is that the goal of the attack was actually to have it happen slowly and enormously -- obviously trying to make warning engineers desperate so they wouldn &apos;t be able to get behind it fast .
the great digital warhead -- we got a glimpse of it by looking at very precisely data and data structures .
so for example , number 164 , it &apos;s very sticking out of this code ; you can &apos;t miss it .
i started working through scientific literature on how these centrifuge are built in nateness , and found that they &apos;re structured in what we call the cascades , and each cascade contains 164 centrifuge .
so that made sense , it fit together .
and it got even better .
these centrifuge in iran are divided into 15 so-called levels .
and guess what we found in the code of attacks ?
it &apos;s an almost identical structure .
so again , this fit really well .
and this gave us great confidence for the one we studied here .
well , don &apos;t get me wrong , it didn &apos;t just work like that .
these results have been achieved through several weeks of hard work .
and often we just ran into a dead end and we had to recollect ourselves .
anyway , we found that both digital warheads actually contributed to the same goal , but from different directions .
the little warhead takes over a cascade , and turns the rotors down and slows them down , and the big warhead comes into interaction with six cascades , and manipulates valves .
so , by and large , we &apos;re very confident that we &apos;ve actually determined what the goal is .
it &apos;s nateness , and it &apos;s just nateness .
so we don &apos;t have to worry that other targets could be hit by stuxnet .
here &apos;s something really cool that we discovered -- blew me out of the socks .
down there is the gray box , and up there you see the centrifuge .
now , what this thing does is it captures the lovely values of sensors -- so for example , from pressure-sensors and vibration sensors -- and it provides legitimate code that continues to happen while attacking , with false data .
and in fact , this false data from stuxnet is already taken before .
so it &apos;s just like in hollywood movies , where , during the pursuit , the surveillance system is fed with pre-recorded video recording .
that &apos;s cool , isn &apos;t it ?
the idea here , obviously , is not just to overlist the machine operators in the control room .
in fact , it &apos;s much more dangerous and much more aggressive .
the idea is to overlist a digital security system .
we need digital security systems where a human machine operator can &apos;t respond fast enough .
so for example , in a power station , if the big steam turbine becomes fast , you have to open depositing valves within milliseconds .
of course , this cannot be done by a human machine leader .
so this is where we need digital security systems .
and if they &apos;re at risk , really bad things can happen .
the power plant can explode .
and not the machine leaders , nor the security system will notice it .
this is scary .
but it gets worse .
and what i &apos;m saying now is very important .
think about it . this attack is generic .
he has nothing to do with centrifuge , with uranization .
so for example , he would work just as well -- at a power station or at a car factory .
it &apos;s generic .
and you don &apos;t have to -- as the attacker -- you don &apos;t have to put the user data on a usb key , as we saw at stuxnet .
you could also use ordinary worm technology to spread .
you just have to spread it as far as you can .
and if you do that , you end up with a cyber-weapon of mass destruction .
that &apos;s the consequence we need to face .
so unfortunately , the biggest number of goals for these attacks is not in the middle east .
they &apos;re in the united states , in europe and japan .
so all these green areas , these are the most targeted environments .
we need to face the consequences , and we need to start to prepare ourselves .
