this is a representation of your brain . your brain can be divided into two halves .
that &apos;s the left half , which is the logical side and then the right half , which is the intuitive side .
if we had a measure to measure the aptitudes of each hemisphere , we could show their brain .
for example , this would be somebody who is completely logical .
this would be somebody who is completely intuitive .
now , where would you place your brain at this scale ?
some of us may have chosen for one of these extremes , but i think for most people in the audience , your brain looks something like this with a high aptitute that &apos;s at the same time in both hemisphere .
it &apos;s not like they &apos;re both exclusive or something like that .
they can be logical and intuitive .
and so i think of myself as one of the people , along with the most other experimental quantum physicists , who need a good proportion of logic to put together the complex ideas .
but at the same time , we need a good deal of intuition to actually do the experiments .
how do we develop these intuitions ? well , we love to play with things .
so we go out and play with it and then see how it responds , and then we start to develop our intuition there .
they basically do the same thing .
so one of the intuitions that they &apos;ve developed over the years is probably that one thing can only be in one place at the same time .
i mean , it can sound strange to think about that thing is in two different places at the same time , but they haven &apos;t been born with this idea , they &apos;ve developed it .
i remember watching a child play on a floor threshold .
he was another little kid , and he didn &apos;t do very well at it all the time .
but i bet he taught a very valuable lesson with the ground threshold , which is that the big things don &apos;t just leave you behind , and they stay in one place .
and this is a great conceptual model of the world , as long as they &apos;re not a particle physicist .
it would be a terrible model for a particle physicist because they don &apos;t play with the gays of the land , they play with these little strange particles .
and when you play with your particles , you find all kinds of weird things -- like flying directly through walls , or that at the same time you can be in two different places .
and so they wrote down all these observations , and they called them the theory of quantum mechanics .
this was the state of physics a few years ago ; it took quantum mechanics to describe the small , tiny particles .
but it didn &apos;t need them to describe the great everyday objects around us .
this didn &apos;t like my intuition , and maybe just because i don &apos;t play with particles that often .
well , i sometimes play with them , but not very often .
and i &apos;ve never seen them .
i mean , nobody has ever seen a particle .
but my logical side didn &apos;t like it either .
because if all of these particles are made of particles and all of these particles follow the rules of quantum mechanics , shouldn &apos;t just follow everything the rules of quantum mechanics ?
i don &apos;t see a reason why it shouldn &apos;t be that way .
so i &apos;d feel really better about the whole thing if we could kind of show that everyday objects also follow the rules of quantum mechanics .
so a few years ago , i set out to do that .
i created one .
this is the first object you can see that was in the quantum mechanical superposition .
so what we &apos;re looking at here is a tiny computer chip .
and you can see that green dot there in the middle there .
this is the piece of metal i &apos;m going to talk about in a moment .
this is a picture of the object .
here i &apos;m expanding it a little bit . we &apos;re looking into the center right here .
and here &apos;s a really big recording of this little piece of metal .
so what we look at is a little piece of metal that &apos;s shaped like a springboard , and it &apos;s over the edge .
so i made this thing in a similar way that you make a computer chip .
i went to a clean room with new silicon slices , and i racked on all the big devices for 100 hours .
for the last little bit , i had to build my own machine -- to get this kind of swimming pool of hole and get this thing .
this thing has the ability to be in the quantum mechanical superposition , but it needs a little help to do it .
look , let me give you an analogy .
you know how uncomfortable it is to be in a full elevator ?
i mean , when i &apos;m alone in the elevator , i do all kinds of weird things , but then other people enter , and i listen to all these things because i don &apos;t want to bother them with , or frankly , they go away .
so quantum mechanics says that unmoving objects also feel the same .
the fellow riders for inmobile objects are not just human , but also light that shines at them , and the wind that passes past them and the heat of the space .
and so we knew that if we wanted to see that this piece of metal acts mechanically , we had to throw out all the passengers .
and then we did .
we turned the light off , put it in a vacuum , suck out all the air , cooling it up until almost now , all the way down on the elevator , the piece of metal was free to behave as it wanted .
so we measured his movement .
we found that it &apos;s really moving strange .
instead of just being quiet there , it vibrated . the way it vibrated was sort of like this -- like a wider and coherent bubble .
by giving him a little push , we were able to make it vibrate at the same time , not vibrate -- something that &apos;s only allowed in quantum mechanics .
so what i &apos;m going to tell you about is what &apos;s truly fantastic .
what does it mean for an object at the same time to vibrate and not vibrate ?
let &apos;s think about the atoms .
so the first case : all the trillion atoms that make up the piece of metal are still there , and at the same time the atoms are moving up and down .
just to precise times , you agree .
they &apos;re delocated the rest of the time .
that means that every atom at the same time is in two different places , which means at the same time that the entire piece of metal is in two different places .
i think that &apos;s really cool .
really .
this was worth me for all of this year in the clean room , because , you know , check this out , the scale difference between a single atom and this piece of metal is about the same as the difference between the piece of metal and you .
so if a single atom can be in two different places at the same time , this piece of metal can be in two different places , why not you ?
i mean , that &apos;s just what my logical side says .
so , imagine that you &apos;re in several places at the same time , how would that feel ?
how would your mind mind be delocated in the space ?
there &apos;s another aspect of history .
when we warmed it up , turned on the light and looked at the box , we saw that the piece of metal was always there in a piece .
and so i had to develop this new intuition that it looks like all the objects in the elevator are actually just quantum objects made together in a small space .
you hear a lot of talk about how quantum mechanics say that everything is connected to everything .
well , that &apos;s not quite right .
there &apos;s more to it , it &apos;s even deeper .
so , these connections , their connections with all the things around them , are literally defining who they are , and this is the profound and strange quantum mechanics .
