in 2007 , i decided that we should conceptualize how we think about economic development .
it should be our goal that if families think about where they live and want to work , they will be given the opportunity to choose between at least one hand of different cities that everybody competes for new residents .
right now , we &apos;re far from that goal .
there are billions of people in the developing world who are not even available to a single city that she would welcome .
but the amazing thing about cities is they &apos;re worth so much more than they &apos;re building them .
so we could end the world very easily with a dumb , maybe even hundreds of new cities .
now this may sound absurd to you as far as you &apos;ve never thought about new cities .
you know , just exchange the construction of apartments against cities .
imagine if half of the people who want to live in homes do this already ; half of them don &apos;t yet .
you could try and expand the capacity of the apartments that existed .
but you know what they &apos;re going to be inserting , in these homes and their environment , there are laws to avoid complaining and deflecting from exhaustion .
so it turns out it &apos;s very difficult to come up with all these extensions .
but you could go to a whole new place , build a whole new block of housing , assuming that the laws would support you and not prevent you .
so i &apos;ve proposed that governments create new surfaces that provide enough space for a city and give them a name : charter cities .
i found out later that , for example , around the same time , jafour and octavio were thinking about the challenge of a reform in honduras .
they knew that every year about 75,000 hondurans could leave their country to go to the united states , and they wanted to know what they could do to make sure that these people could stay in their country and do exactly the same thing in honduras .
