my role is to explain to people how wonderful the new technologies that happened will be . and i thought , since i &apos;m among friends , i would tell you what i really think . and also try to look back and understand what &apos;s really happening here with these incredible leaps forward , which are so fast that we can barely keep up with .
i &apos;m going to start by showing you a single boring slide for a second .
... if you could just show the slide for a second .
this is a slide i randomly chose from my folder .
i &apos;m not talking about the details of the slide , but rather the general shape .
this slide shows you data from an analysis of the risc processors compared to the performance of a local area network .
what &apos;s interesting here is that this slide , like some of the others we often arrive at in our field , are kind of on a semi-logarithmic curve .
in other words , every step here corresponds to a power in the scale .
and this is a novelty that we need to use this guy scale on semi-logarithmic curves in the field of technology .
something very strange is happening here .
this is basically what i &apos;m going to talk about .
so , if you could turn on the light again .
a little brighter , because i &apos;m going to draw something on the paper in a minute .
now , why do we draw graphs in technology on semi-logarithmic curves ?
the reason for that is , if i were to draw it on a normal curve where , say , these are the years , so the timeline of a species , and this is any measure of the technology i wanted to represent with a graph , the graph will get silly .
they then look like this .
and that doesn &apos;t tell us much .
now if i wanted to record another technology , let &apos;s say a transportation technology , it would be very irrational on the semi-logarithmic scale , in the form of a flat line .
but when something like this happens , it changes the qualitative circumstances .
so if the transportation technology were going to continue as fast as the microprocessor technology , then we could get in a taxi tomorrow and in 30 seconds we would be in tokyo .
but it &apos;s not so fast .
this has never happened before in the history of technology , this kind of recursive growth , where the scale is exponentially increasing every few years .
the question i want to ask you now is , if you look at these exponential curves , you see , they &apos;re not going to go forever .
it &apos;s not possible that everything will evolve as fast as it is now on forever .
there are two choices .
either it becomes a classic s-curve like this , until something whole new comes along , or this is going to happen .
that &apos;s it , for example .
well , i &apos;m an optimist , so i think something like this is going to happen .
is that true , then that means that we &apos;re in the middle of a transition right now .
we &apos;re on this line here , in a transition from the world to a new kind of world .
so the question i want to ask , and i often ask myself , is this new world going to be good ?
what &apos;s this new state that the world is starting to take on ?
because the transition seems to be very , very confusing when you &apos;re in the middle of it .
when i was a kid , there was a future somewhere in the year 2000 , and people often talked about what would happen in 2000 .
now we have a conference where people talk about the future , and you realize the future is still in 2000 .
we &apos;re not going to go further than that .
so in other words , the future has shrunk by a year since i was in the world .
i think the reason for that is that we realize that anything is going on .
the transition happens . we can all feel it .
and we know right now that it just doesn &apos;t make any sense to try to look into the future , because everything will be so different that a simple high degree of what we &apos;re doing now simply doesn &apos;t make sense .
i want to talk about what that might be , this transition that we &apos;re in right now .
to do this , i &apos;m going to talk first about a couple of other things that really have nothing to do with technology or computers .
because i think to really understand this , we have to go back and look at the thing on a longer scale of time .
and that &apos;s what i want to look at on the earth &apos;s scale of life .
i think the big picture makes sense when you divide it into some billions of steps .
so let &apos;s go back , 2.5 billion years . the earth was a big , sterile stone lump with a lot of chemicals on it .
now if you look at the way these chemicals were organized , it gives us a pretty good picture of how they did it .
i also think there are theories that start to understand how everything started with rna , but i &apos;m going to tell you a simplistic story of what &apos;s going on at that time is that little oil droplet was flipping around , which had different kinds of chemicals in it .
some of these oil droplet contained a special combination of chemicals that allowed them to integrate other chemicals from outside , and to grow .
all of them were like this started to divide .
these little oil droplet were the most primitive cell form in the sense .
but these oil droplet weren &apos;t about alive today , because each of them was just a small accidental recipe of chemicals .
and every time it divided , the chemicals in it have spread to countless quantities .
so each droplet was a little different .
in fact , the droplet that had one for growth grew more optimal composition than others , and more and more chemicals from outside and divided up faster .
so these tends to survive longer , and they multiplied at a larger scale .
so this is just a very simple chemical form of life , but more interesting , when these droplet learned a trick about abstraction .
in any way that we don &apos;t quite understand yet , these droplet have learned the ability to write down information .
they &apos;ve learned to store the recipe of the cell as information in a particular chemical form that we call dna .
in other words , in this mindless , evolutionary way , they found a way to allow them to sign down what they were made of , so that this information could be stored and copied .
the amazing thing about this is that this kind of storing information over the course of 2.5 billion years it was born stayed the same .
in fact , the recipe for us , which is our genes , from exactly the same code and the same spelling .
and every being uses the exact same letters and the same code .
we are so far that , just for pleasure , we can write things ourselves in this code .
and i have 100 micrograms of a white pulver that i &apos;m trying to keep in airports of security staff &apos;s attempt .
it &apos;s in it -- what i &apos;ve done is i &apos;ve taken this code -- the code is made up of normal letters that we use to symbolize -- and i &apos;ve written my business card on a piece of dna and i &apos;ve amplified it 10 mexico 22 times .
so if somebody wants a hundred million copies of my business card , i have enough for anyone in this room and even for anyone in the world , and it &apos;s right here .
if i had been a selfish in fact , i would have written it on a virus and released it into the room .
so what &apos;s the next step ?
the sign of dna was an interesting step .
and that &apos;s what these cells did -- that &apos;s what made them happy for another billion years .
but then another very interesting step happened where things became completely different , which is that these cells started communicating and trading information , so that communities emerged from cells .
i don &apos;t know if you knew that , but bacteria can actually exchange their dna .
that &apos;s why , for example , the durability grows into antibiotics .
some bacteria have figured out how to stay away from penicillin and put that information together with other bacteria into the dna , and now we have a lot of bacteria that are resistant to penicillin because the bacteria communicate with each other .
now this communication allowed communities , in a sense , to be in the same boat ; they were synergetically table .
so they either survived together , or they entered together , which meant that if a community was successful , all the individuals of the community were more repeated and preferred by evolution .
the transition site is now where these communities together so close that they decided to write the recipe for the whole community into a sign chain on the dna .
and the next interesting stage took about another billion years .
at that point , we have multi-cellular communities , communities of many different cell types , which act together as a single organism .
in fact , we &apos;re also such a multi-cellular community .
we have lots of cells that are no longer put on their own .
your skin cells are useless without heart cells , muscle cells , brain cells and so on .
so these communities started to evolve , so that the level that evolution was no longer the individual cell , but the whole cell community that we call organism .
the next step has now happened within these communities .
the cell communities started to abstract information again .
and they developed special structures that did nothing but process information within the organism .
and these are the neural structures .
so the neurons are the information processing system that these cell communities have built .
they started to train specialists within the community , special structures , which were responsible for learning , understanding and capturing information .
and this was the brain and the nervous system of these communities .
this gave them an evolutionary advantage .
because at that point , an individual -- learning has now happened within the time of a single organism &apos;s lifespan , rather than through this evolutionary period .
so for example , an organism could learn to eat a particular fruit because it tasted bad and made it sick that last time he ate it .
now this could happen within the lifetime of a single organism , whereas hundreds of thousands of years before that , because this information had to be learned evolutionarily by the individuals who died because of this fruit , because these information processing structures weren &apos;t there .
so the nervous system has the evolutionary process using these special information structures because evolution could now happen within an individual .
she could happen within a time-learning framework .
what happened then is that the individual organisms found a way to communicate with each other .
for example , the most subtle of us know about this type of communication is human language .
it &apos;s a pretty amazing invention when you think about it .
i have a very complicated , messy and confused idea in my head .
i &apos;m sitting here , and basically giving sound to me , gruesome , hoping to create a rather confused idea in your head that has a certain similarity to my original idea .
so we take something very complicated , we turn it into sound , a sequence of sound , and we make something very complicated into the minds of others .
so this is what it &apos;s allowing us to work again as a unified organism .
and what we actually did , we , humanity , is we started to abstract .
we go through the same stages that several cell organisms have gone through -- the abstraction of our methods of holding data on , presenting .
for example , the invention of language was a small step in that direction .
telephony , computers , video users , cd-roms and so on are all our specialized mechanisms that we built in our community to be able to handle this information .
and it connects us all together to something that &apos;s much bigger , and it &apos;s also able to evolve faster than we have been before .
so today , evolution can happen in the time span of microseconds .
you also saw tys &apos;s little evolutionary example , where he showed some evolution in the convolvation program , right in front of your eyes .
so now we &apos;ve removed the time scales .
the first steps in history i &apos;ve told you took one billion years per piece .
the next steps , like the nervous system and the brain , took a few hundred million years .
then the next steps , like language and so on , took less than a million years .
and these next steps , like electronics , seem to take very few decades .
so the process feeds itself , and i think auto-catalytic is the word for it -- when something increases its speed of change .
the more it changes , the faster it changes .
and i think that &apos;s what we see here in this explosion curve .
we see the process that feeds itself .
i live professionally from building computers , and i know that i couldn &apos;t use the mechanism that i use to build computers without the recent advances in computer technology .
my current activity is to design objects with such a high complexity that it &apos;s impossible for me to design them in the traditional sense .
i don &apos;t know what every single transistor is doing in the connection machine .
it has billions of them .
what i do instead , and whatever designers do of thinking machines , is we think at a certain level of abstraction , that this machine , and the machine , of course , does something that overgoes our skills better and faster than we could ever do it ourselves .
and it does it in part with methods that we don &apos;t even really understand .
one of the ways that &apos;s particularly interesting , and which i &apos;ve been using a lot of the time , is evolution itself .
and we install an evolutionary process in this machine that &apos;s going on in the microsecond area .
to give you an example , in the most extreme cases , we can make a program that &apos;s developed from random instructions .
we say , &quot; computers , please generate a hundred million randomly selected sequences of instructions .
now , please perform all of these randomly chosen instructions , perform all of the programs , and then finally choose the ones i &apos;m going to make the next one of my presentations . &quot;
so in other words , i define first what i want .
let &apos;s say i want to make numbers , that would be a simple example that i &apos;ve already used for it .
so there are programs that can be the most numbers that can be done .
of course , the chance with randomly chosen instructions is very small that , by chance , they &apos;ll just sort numbers , so probably none of the instructions will actually do this .
but one of them may , if you &apos;re lucky , put two numbers in the right order .
now i say , &quot; computers , now take those 10 percent of the sequences that i &apos;ve made the next thing i &apos;ve made .
store them off , wipe the rest off .
now all the rest of the world are reproductions that have best sorted numbers .
and it &apos;s a recombination technique , analog to reproduction . &quot;
take two programs , and they make kids through the exchange of their subroutines , and the kids inherit the features of the subroutines from the two programs .
so now i have a new generation of programs that have come from combinations of programs that have come a little closer to the preventions than others .
say , &quot; please repeat this process . &quot;
you reevaluate them .
lead perhaps some mutations .
and try the whole thing again with another generation .
all of these generations take just a few milliseconds to do .
and so i can run through evolution over millions of years in the computer in a few minutes , or more complicated times , a few hours .
finally , i get programs that can perfectly sorrow numbers .
in fact , these programs are so much more efficient than any program i could have ever written by hand .
so when i look at these programs , i can &apos;t tell you how they work .
i tried to understand them .
they &apos;re obscure and strange programs .
but they do the job .
i know and i &apos;m sure they do the job because they come from a series of hundreds of thousands of programs that did the job .
because her life depended on whether they did the job right .
