it may seem strange to you , but i &apos;m a big fan of concrete blocks .
the first concrete blocks were made in 1868 and came up with a simple idea : module from cement with solid measures that fit together .
concrete building blocks became very quickly the world &apos;s most used building unit .
they put us in place to build things bigger than us , buildings , bridges , one stone at a time .
basically , the concrete building block had become the building block of our time .
almost a hundred years later , in 1947 , lego came out with this .
it was called the automatically bonding stone .
and within a few years , lego moved into every household .
it &apos;s been estimated that over 400 billion rocks were produced -- 75 stones for every person on the planet .
they don &apos;t have to be an engineer to create beautiful houses , beautiful bridges or beautiful buildings .
lego made it possible for all of you .
lego basically took the concrete building block , the building block of the world , and made it a building block for our imagination .
in the meantime , at the bell labs , the next revolution was announced , the next building block .
the transistor was a small plastic unit that would take us from a world of static , interconnected building blocks to a world where everything was going to be interactive .
like the concrete block , the transistor allows us to build much larger , more complex cycles , one stone at a time .
but there &apos;s a big difference : the transistor was only for experts .
personally , i don &apos;t accept that the building block of our time is reserved for experts , and so i decided to change that .
eight years ago , i was at the media lab , and i started to explore this idea of how to put the power of engineers in the hands of artists and designers .
a few years ago , i started developing littlebits .
let me show you how they work .
littlebits are electronic modules that have specific function .
they &apos;re preferred to be light , sound , engine and sensor .
and the best part is that they connect with magnets .
that &apos;s how you can &apos;t put them wrong .
the stones are colored .
green is issue , blue is power , pink is input , orange is cable .
so all you have to do is connect a blue and a green one , and you can build a larger cycle very quickly .
they add a blue to a green one , and they can make light .
you can put in a switch in between , and so you &apos;ve created a little dimmer .
take the switch out to put a pulse array , which is here , and they made a little blind .
add this buzzer to it for an extra effect , and they &apos;ve made a noisy machine .
i &apos;m going to stop that .
beyond the simple game , littlebits is actually quite powerful .
instead of having to program , wire or delete , littlebits allow them to code with simple , intuitive gestures .
so to speed up or slow the blind , just turn it on this button , and it makes the momentum faster or slower .
the idea behind littlebits is that it &apos;s a growing library .
we want to put every single interaction in the world into a useful rock .
lights , notes , solar panels , motors -- everything should be available .
we have distributed littlebits to kids , and you see them playing with them .
and it was an incredible experience .
the most beautiful thing is , how do you start to understand the electronics that you surround in your everyday life and that you don &apos;t learn in school ?
how an ipod works , for example , or why the doors of the elevator remain open , or how an ipod responds to touch .
we also brought littlebits to design schools .
so for example , we had no experience for designers with electronic things that started playing with littlebits as a material .
here we see , with filts , paper and water bottles , like geordie ...
a few weeks ago , we risd littlebits , and we gave them a few designers who had no technical experience -- just cardboard , wood and paper -- and told them , &quot; do something . &quot;
here &apos;s an example of a project they did , a movable confetti cannon .
but wait , this is really my favorite project .
it &apos;s a play-dough hummer who &apos;s afraid in darkness .
for these non-engineers , littlebits became another material , electronics just became another material .
and we want to make this material available to all of them .
so littlebits are open source .
you can go to the website , download all the design papers and make them yourself .
we want the world of creators , the inventor , who encourages contributors , because this world in which we live , this interactive world , belongs to us .
so , pull it off and start inventing it .
thank you .
